ce:section.ce:para:
To further understand the energy storage mechanism involved in this study, molecular dynamics modeling related to the ion distribution between the electrodes have been carried out using reactive force field (ReaxFF) parameters as detailed in references [49,50]. The simulations were conducted in a two symmetrical electrode system with CNF mats as positive and negative electrodes under a potential charge of 1.0 V. Results in Fig. 7
                         show the comparative distribution of ions in KOH (Fig. 7a-b) and mixed electrolyte (Fig. 7c-d) in the proximity of positive and negative electrodes. According to the Stern model, the electric double layer consists of two regions for ion distribution: (i) the Stern layer or compact layer also called the inner region (denoted as x1
                        ), and (ii) the diffuse layer (denoted as x2
                        ) [51] (Fig. 7j, KOH). In KOH electrolyte the first layer next to the electrodes (x1
                        ), the positive electrode showed great attraction towards OH– ions, and the negative electrode showed high affinity to K+ ions (Fig. 7a-b). For the mixed electrolyte (Fig. 7c-d), ferricyanide ions was present in the Stern layer (Fig. 7c). Unlike OH–, there is ferricyanide ions outside of the Stern layer (Fig. 7d), potentially due to the low concentration of K3Fe(CN)6 (0.01 M), compared to 6 M KOH. At the negative electrode, the strong distribution of water between K+ and the surface of the electrode may strongly suggest the solvation of K+ ions and the continuous hydration of the porous electrode.

To analyze the effect of K3Fe(CN)6 on pseudocapacitance, the K+ and OH– ion distribution was plotted for KOH and the mixed electrolytes. At the positive electrode, the ion density distribution of OH– in the mixed electrolyte (dashed line) was reduced compared to KOH (solid line) (Fig. 7e). Note that the x1
                         layer in the mixed electrolyte shows the presence of both OH– and ferricyanide ions (Fig. 7c), revealing the presence of ferricyanide ions next to the electrode surface repelled some OH– to the diffuse layer (x2
                        ) farther than the original OH– distribution in KOH. The adsorption of ferricyanide ions to the electrode “breaks” the Stern layer compacted with OH– ions, enabling faradic reaction between the ferricyanide and electrode interface (Fig. 7i, KOH + K3Fe(CN)6, x1+xf
                        ). Ferricyanide ions strongly adsorbed on the carbon electrode's surface, enhancing redox capacity of the positive electrode in the mixed electrolyte, resulting in increase in pseudocapacitance from combined effect of pseudocapacitance enhancement of the redox electrolyte and the increased double-layer capacitance.
